segments.text: I'm down in Conroe and have the very great honor of chatting with Bob Rucker about his memories of being a student and then being a key member of the staff at A&M.
Bob, now check yours.
Okay, Haskell, I'll do the best I can.
I'll record some things.
Bob, as we begin, for the sake of someone that might not know your background,
begin by describing where you grew up, family background, where was home before coming to A&M.
I grew up in the country town of Franklin, Texas, 35 miles northeast of A&M.
And my mother died when I was a year and a half old.
And my grandmother took me and my sister, who was three, to raise.
And she was 47 years old and twice with her.
So we lived in the country town hotel.
And from the time we could walk, we had a job to do.
And I met everybody in the world.
I never met a stranger.
I put people to bed at night as a night clerk and never remember a thing about the next morning.
But I have one sister, and as I said, our mother died when I was a year and a half old from flu epidemic of World War I.
And my father lived a long time and remarried and was never part of my life, really.
It was our grandmother and an aunt and two girl cousins and my sister.
I grew up with
Six women.
So anyway, then I went to A&M.
What led you to go to A&M?
Why there?
We didn't know anything else but A&M, the whole family.
If Robert ever went to school, that's where he was going.
And we tried to go and wanted to go, but we didn't have any money.
And finally, I got a job, Mr. Hensel, Mr. F. W. Hensel,
who was just like a father to me all the years, and still is.
I still respect him very much, even though he'd been gone a few years.
He gave me a job in the greenhouse, and I got to work an extra hour every day because I had to run the heat and ventilate the greenhouse at night.
I didn't know it, but that was quite a job to give a freshman.
And anyway, I averaged working 22 hours a week.
So when I graduated, personnel said, look, you've worked more than half time, so you're going to get five years prior credit for Social Security.
So I took it.
Now, did you go visit the campus before enrolling as a freshman?
Yes.
I went in the fall of

spring of 32 but i couldn't didn't get to go to school until two years later in 34. but uh i am i remember the campus from the very beginning and of course i have enjoyed the campus many years there's a lot of history there describe the campus when you've what it what was there when you first got there what did it look like
looked like heaven to an old country boy.
I never saw as many flowers and different kinds of flowers in my life.
I met Mr. Hensel.
Kept that campus blooming all the time with flyers.
We had sometimes 700, 800 petunias in one bed.
And there in front of the academic building, what I guess is now Jack, what's his name?
Jack Williams.
Jack Williams building.
Well, at the time I was there,
there was a small hedge in front of that balustrade.
And when I got down there, you couldn't see the balustrade.
It wasn't anything there.
It was big, high arborvitaes.
And two great big parterre beds on each end of that big plaza, where the flagpole is now, or was then there.
But I cut those arborvitaes down.
They were 40 feet tall.
And people had never seen that pile of straight.
And also, the board wanted me to bring the flowers back to the campus.
So Tom Cherry came up to Oklahoma to look at some high-rise dorms.
And he saw that what we called a test garden, a very small garden at the time, it has since grown into a big garden
And has been endowed by alumni every year for a big display of chrysanthemums.
And it was so spectacular three or four years ago that the American chrysanthemums that he was meeting in Dallas drove up there to see it.
And that precipitated the endowment or the upkeep of it by some alumni.
I've been gone from Oklahoma for long.
But anyway, the story of, we were going to give Ms. Johnson, the Northwest Chapter of the American Society of Landscape Architects, was going to give Ms. Johnson a citation for her beauty bills.
She couldn't be there to accept it, so Ms.
Rudder accepted it.
She sat next to me all during the meeting, and we talked.
She got back home, she said,
Earl already told the board if they'd found the man, he'd hire him.
So she got back home and says, I found the man for you.
And she put my name in the pot.
Oh, good.
That's how I got back.
Well, let's go back, though, to your freshman years.
When you came to enroll, how did you come?
How did you get there?
And what stuff did you bring with you?
What clothing?
How much money?
Somebody brought me down in the car.
I don't know who it was.
I don't remember.
I didn't have much clothes.
Nobody had much clothes during the Depression.
I knew they were going to have uniforms.
I didn't need many clothes, and that's why, thank goodness for the military, for a lot of reasons.
I arrived on campus, and Mr. Hensel...
This was the fall of 34.
Fall of 34.
Mr. Hensel gave me the job in the greenhouse.
He told my aunt, he says, that guy can get more plants than my seniors do.
Of course, I'd grown everything in Hastings Seed Catalog.
I think it would come in January each year.
And my grandmother said, now, Robert, pick out what you want, and we'll order it.
And on one side of the hotel, we had about a half-acre garden.
I raided all the vegetables that we used in the hotel.
Other side, I could have anything I wanted, and we'd have a flower.
So I grew.
A lot of things, I didn't know they wouldn't grow in practice.
I just planned the way they grew.
And every now and then somebody said, well, what is that?
Well, it can't grow here.
I said, it is.
Nobody told me I couldn't grow it.
It's in the catalog, so I planned it.
Do you remember how much money you brought with you when you were enrolled as a freshman?
Practically none, I'll tell you that.
We borrowed, we got a loan.
from what they called the Farmer Students Association at that time.
And it was a very small, it was hard to get a loan.
But with my aunt underwriting the note, we got a loan from the, did we call it Exitutes of Farmers?
I think we called it Farmers.
Anyway.
I just have to come in here and say hello to these two.
Thank you.
Describe Mr. Hensel as a person, physically, and what his nature was.
One of the greatest men I ever knew in my life.
He came from San Antonio and was used to lots of flowers in San Antonio.
He put them on the campus.
He had a good grower, Mr. Monosmith, P.B.
Monosmith, M-O-N-O-S-M-I-T-H.
lived in what we call Candy Hill.
It's up north of the power plant there, as it does the faculty members.
And Mr. Hensel was like a father to me.
He found out that I knew the plants, and that I wanted to work, and I wasn't afraid to work, and so he gave me plenty to do.
But he also, that's the news.
Now, did he, did you come to A&M thinking you were going to major in... Mary Murchin, line one.
Mary Murchin, line one.
Did you come to A&M planning to major in horticulture, floriculture?
I came to A&M to major in floriculture, but it wasn't in the floriculture department.
The nearest thing to it was landscape art.
And there's a good story there.
He is the father of landscape architecture in the Southwest.
Now, he knew his financial support was Dean Kyle.
So he knew also, I think he was a student enough to know that it wouldn't take very much to change from landscape art to landscape architecture.
But he knew that if he didn't keep it in the College of Agriculture, he wouldn't have any fun in it.
That led to the development of landscape architecture as such.
Mary Merchant, please dial extension 104.
Mary Merchant, 104.
They distribute our medicine here.
Anytime we need a pill, they come to us.
No, when I found Mr. Hensel, I thought I'd really found, well, he always was the finest man I knew.
He had high standards.
And he expected his students to be high standards.
And we worked hard.
If you worked hard, like he wanted you to, you made your grades and so forth.
We had two or three old boys that didn't want to work as hard as he did.
And they named him Butch.
Very disrespectful.
Anyway, they have a funny thing over in the College of Architecture where they've been honoring people.
And they left Hensel out.
So I corrected that real quick the next year.
I wrote out all the background and gave it to him.
But he was my real mentor, and I followed him all the rest of my life.
Every time I'd go back to campus, there were two people I'd go to see.
I'd go to see Mr. Hensel and Mrs. Walton.
We'll chat about her later.
How did you get assigned to the Corps?
What outfit and how did you get oriented?
Well, I was assigned to A Infantry.
There were a couple of boys from Franklin in the Corps.
One was Taylor Wilkins, a football player, and he wasn't very military.
But anyway, that's why I was assigned to A Infantry.
And A Infantry lived in Hart Hall.
I lived in a little room behind the greenhouse to take care of the stuff at night.
And it's clear across the campus.
And I would work till
5 o'clock, no, 6 o'clock, and just barely make it in time for formation, for me to formate.
In fact, I was usually late.
And two sophomores whipped me, paged me all year, because they said I never did, I couldn't get to me to formate on time.
And finally, the Red Company commander, Ray Thompson, from the right warden,
Caught them patting me one day.
They're supposed to quit at Christmas.
It's well up in the spring.
And he said, now, why do you feel he's a fish rocker?
Well, he never gets to the meal farm ages on time.
Well, he said, did you know he worked till 6 o'clock?
No, he didn't tell us.
I said, you didn't ask us.
And I said, I couldn't tell you anyway.
I said, this I'm not allowed to even think.
I was insulting them right back.
And well, from then on, they left me alone.
He said, if I catch you with a hazing fish right again, you'll wish you hadn't been born.
So that was over with.
They kept asking me all year, why didn't you tell us that you were?
You didn't ask me.
It's that simple.
Anyway, we won the best drill company two years in a row, and we were all very proud of that.
They called it the Howe Trophy, and I know we worked our socks off on that.
Now, you all would fall in in front of Hart Hall and march.
No, Sabisa.
Sabisa.
Describe the routine in the dining hall for fish.
Pretty rough.
You didn't get any dessert for 38 days.
That's your class year.
And if you didn't know the number, you'd start all over.
And somebody, I never knew the number.
So we didn't have any dessert until well after Christmas.
And that kind of stuff.
I stopped.
But it was all family style.
And you...
Well, you passed everything back and forth.
Mary Merchant, please dial extension 104.
Mary Merchant, extension 104.
A fish ate after everybody else.
And every now and then, somebody would do this.
Wave their hands.
Well, if a girl was there, if an opposite had a girl, and boy, did he get upset.
Somebody crawled under there and put muscular issues.
And that didn't go over too well with the upperclassmen.
And you were supposed to bring things out of the mess hall to the upperclassmen.
Friends, we had rolls.
Oh, I guess six or eight in a bunch, you know.
And you'd stick them under your arm and walk out.
And every now and then, somebody would put a pie in their stomach, you know, and pull a shirt over it.
I had a real good friend, Freddie Knapp, from K-N-A-P-P, from Calvert, and he put a cherry pie in there one day, and the sergeant saw it, and he got rid of me and said, how are you, sonny?
I'm telling you.
Smacked him in the stomach.
All kinds of pranks like this played.
The worst thing they did was some of the vet boys
if they were really in for somebody on the court.
They'd take the genitals of the horse and put it on a plate and sit in front of him.
Well, it was raunchy.
Golly, it was raunchy.
What kind of tricks did Aggies play in the dining hall in those days?
You mentioned one or two.
What about some others?
Well, let me think.
the making you carry things out.
You know, a half a pound of milk in a little bottle would just fit in your sock.
That would carry that out.
You had to bring something out.
You were detailed to bring something out.
And if you didn't, it was pretty bad.
But they get hard on you.
But I guess the worst thing was the bird.
Every time there was a girl,
old boy had his girl down for the weekend, so he could depend on getting the bird some way.
But that's about it.
Outside of not having any kush, you had to get up at 4 Reveille and call them to attention, battalion attention, so many more days to kush.
so that you could have some dessert.
Well, we always had two old boys and a half that never could remember when that day would come, how many days.
So we'd start over nearly about every week or ten days, we'd have to start over on counting the days.
Let's see, what were the nicknames y'all gave to the various foods and drinks?
See, cow was milk, wasn't it?
Yes, cow was milk.
Was bull neck
Bullock was any kind of meat.
You could have had any meat or been with somebody else.
We would do anything to insult an upper class, in particular sophomores.
We were detailed to insult a sophomore.
Knowing full well we were going to pay for it later.
We had one old boy with a great big butt on him, and he said something about blowing out your eyes, and Osama said, yeah, O2 is big enough, you know.
There wasn't any place for cool heads out here in that time of day.
Were there cush questions then?
Cush questions.
And I've heard some of the folks in a few years later, like one of the cush questions was how many stars are there in the Texas flag?
And if you answered one, they said, no, there's two.
There's one on each side.
And if you said two, they'd say, no, there's one.
It goes all the way through.
I haven't heard that one.
Well, that was another gimmick.
If you couldn't answer the question the way they wanted you to, then you didn't get any kush.
You didn't get any kush, that's right.
Well, some people never got any kush until way up after Christmas.
You see, all hazing was supposed to stop at Christmas.
You were able to get two licks, Merry Christmas, and that was it.
Well, because I never could get the meal formation on time, they didn't quit Christmas.
I went home because I didn't want to sit down at all.
Now, did you, you lived in that room over by the greenhouses all the time?
All four years.
Did you come over there to fall in for Morning Child?
Everything.
The whole thing?
He got, I wouldn't think of asking him not to.
I was behind the block of the dining hall entrance we went in.
But I was gonna be in every formation.
In fact, I was determined to be a good fish.
And I worked at being a good fish.
And I had a good time.
I had more fun, I guess, as a freshman than anybody, because I didn't care.
What was special about your outfit?
Well, we were very, very military.
Our company had won the Howe Trophy, best real company in the infantry the year before, and our captain
company commander, Red Thompson from Throckmorton, was determined that we were going to win again, and we did.
But we had an awful time with one fish.
We had a fish named Fish Mill from Dallas, and he had been in ROTC in high school, and he thought he was the cock of the walk down there, that they could win that trophy without any help.
We got all lined up, ready to go, and we looked over in the rear rank, and there's Fish Mills.
He had had his whole uniform in the shower.
He looked like the wrath of God.
And so Ronnie Sorensen, our executive director, he's still there.
I think he's still there.
Wonderful person.
And we looked back over there, and he said,
you know, if he's absent, we'll lose less points than we'll do if he's here.
So they sent him upstairs.
And somebody put him in a waste paper basket in the room through there where he couldn't get away.
And he had to watch it.
We had two people absent, but we lost less points since they'd both been there.
And anyway, we worked hard.
And we were happy.
We won the Al trophy.
I think now they have another kind of a trophy for it.
Describe a typical day of classes.
What time did it begin?
What was the routine for the day and so forth?
Roughly, I had chemistry.
What time did you get up normally?
Oh, I'd get up around, we had to get up around six o'clock.
We went to bed with the bugle, got up with the bugle.
I would have, I had chemistry lecture in Claycross Hall at the gym.
I had PE, and I'd run over that way to PE and then run back to English.
And let me see, what else did I, we were, I was either in class or at work six, let's see, nine hours a day.
And that's when they, when they got through, when they,
everything tabled up.
They said, well, you've worked more than half time, so you get five years in mass credit and social security, which is all right with me.
What did you do after Evening Chow?
Well, you went back to the company.
I'm not sure that I remember what we did after Evening Chow.
I said we had
We all were in some kind of a bull session with the upperclassmen.
We had twin, identical twins in our outfit, the Mountain Brothers.
Freddie was a freshman.
They were from Calvert, Parker and Gilson.
And they had a long suit the first week or two.
And they'd park one on the first floor and one on the second floor.
And you'd walk in and the second floor would say, hello, Mr. Napp.
Who the hell are you, freshman?
I never saw you before in my life.
They were identical to us, and we didn't know it.
And I did know one from the other.
But they were a good body.
They moved to the Valley and ran a Chevrolet company down there.
What did you wear to class?
Describe the uniforms of the 1930s.
Well, we wore just
khaki pants that were scratched, and wool shirts that were bad.
They were all government-issued stuff.
And the blouse had blue lapel on them, because that meant you were two years, first two years in the military.
Then you bought your stuff in junior, senior year, if you were taking advanced military.
But it was just very plain and coarse and rough.
Scratchy.
All right, what about for ceremonies?
What did you all wear for reviews and so forth?
Freshman and sophomore wore the blouses with the blue lapels as non-contractors.
When you got to be juniors and seniors, you bought your own, and you had the regular dress shirts, pink pants, and Sam Brown belt, and a regular old hat.
We didn't get the caps.
I don't think we got caps until the Corps took a real late.
What about some of the pranks, jokes, good bull that Aggies played on each other?
Well, of course, everybody got drowned out one or two times.
One time I borrowed a hose from the greenhouse and took it over and put it on the third floor and turned it loose.
And it just looked like Niagara Falls coming down the steps.
Gaga Commons, I don't know his first name.
We called him Gaga.
He was a fifth-year senior.
And he decided he would haze me one night.
And he took a baseball bat and hit me so hard.
I said, I'm about to go back up there.
I just kept on going down the steps.
And I left him.
And then I lived literally in that greenhouse area to take care of at night.
The bunch of boys soon found out that they'd come running down that road and come into the greenhouse and crawl around the benches and stay there.
So they did.
And I thought Mr. Hinton might object, but he didn't.
He wasn't for hazing anyway.
So he didn't object to that.
Did y'all steal anybody's footlocker, any of your CO's footlocker?
No.
Didn't?
We didn't do that kind of pranks.
We had one, I'll never forget, Lord have mercy.
Across the street from Hart is Goodwin.
I don't know if it's still there or not.
But they had big furnaces in it, and every night the chimney suits would come in by the droves.
And we had a senior...
A. Gibb Trimley, T-R-I-M-B-L-E-Y, who was a major on the Corps staff.
Well, you couldn't touch him with a 10-foot pole.
So one night, somebody detailed us just to fix him up.
So we caught about two or three sacks of those stinking chimneysweeps.
And we didn't open the door, knock on the door, and walk in and dump them in your room.
You have never seen such a mess in your life.
Of course, we had to clean it all up.
And you know about ratting the rooms.
Just drive it, please.
All right.
The sophomore was having a class meeting.
And while they were gone, we were supposed to take their room apart.
And we didn't know what taking a room apart was until we had our class meeting.
And they took our room apart.
They even took the bed springs apart.
We actually never got that thing put back together.
But when wethat was called ratting the rooms.
And you took it apart like you couldn't believe.
And Hart Hall was lucky to have a blazed tile.
We didn't quite tear it up.
But you know, we had to put up a room to buy it.
And I put up a room to buy it and ran into that room over the greenhouse.
Because this is as darned to a room.
But...
Describe that...
You put up a room to put it, but nobody ever got a room to put it back.
There was much damage done to the dormitory during the year.
They used all that money and then some to put it back together.
Describe that room you lived in over by the greenhouse.
What was in it?
How big was it?
It was just big enough to get a bunk bed and one end of it.
And it was a regular bunk bed, and we had just plain old planks put together for a closet in there and a desk.
And that was all.
I didn't have a bath.
I had to go a half block up a street.
I wish I could remember the dormitory's name.
You'll have to get it for me.
And I'd take a bath.
There was a field artillery there, and I was an infantry freshman that nobody knew.
And I'd go up to this old boy's room I knew in class and take a bath.
Finally, I finally got aI had a commodefinally got a shower in there, and it was water you turned steam in to get it hot.
Of course, you had to be careful you didn't scald yourself.
Anyway, we finally got thatI guess my senior year.
The, how did things change for you as a sophomore?
How was life different?
Well, I didn't believe in hazing freshmen, so I didn't haze any fish.
I never did haze any fish.
And I, well, of course, I didn't, you didn't have much trouble during sophomore.
If you'd been a good fish and
which I tried to do.
I did have a corporal rank, even though I lived clear over there.
That's because of, I guess, of what I did in the company.
And also because I liked military.
But change didn't take very much for me.
I was a squad leader.
That gave me some more training.
And then when I started to be in the junior year, they decided I was a day student instead of a dormitory student, even though I paid dormitory rent.
So I decided I was a day student, and they were going to put all the day students in one outfit.
So they had three companies, a headquarters, a headquarters second time, headquarters third time,
Anyway, there were three day companies, and one of my very best friends who was filing with us at the Experiment Station, Tom, wait a minute, I forgot his name.
Anyway, there were three day companies, and we all had a company.
I was the first sergeant of one, and Tom McMillan,
I was sergeant one, and I forget who the other one was.
Anyway, we had, for three years, we had day student companies.
Even though I stayed in that room and paid rural dormitory rent, because I didn't live in the dorms per se, I was considered a day student.
Did you live in that room over the greenhouse all four years?
All four years.
I had the responsibility of not, well,
seeing the heat and ventilation was done on the greenhouse, and all we had for heat was cutting steam, live steam, into cold water again.
Hot water system, which is a good system.
It's a good level system, even temperature, until you boiled it all over and started over again.
And I took care of the greenhouse and ventilation.
But I would have to go from that room, clear the hard hall, to make meal formations.
And that's why many times they'd catch me about selling when they played to the colors, and I'd have to stop and salute.
And then by the time I got to that,
They were already here in Squad Z and going to the time missile.
And that's what those two sophomores equipped me for.
I was never on time for formation.
And when the company commander finally called away, I was free.
As you began your courses as a freshman,
What were some of the most memorable courses that you took?
The only course I liked, I had two of them.
I liked botany and entomology.
I made an A-plus on the final exam in entomology.
I'll never forget that, because the doctor, the teacher wouldn't believe me.
He said, I can't believe that you know the names, the names of all these insects.
I said, well, that's what you taught us, you know.
And that was, I loved entomology and I loved botany.
And of course you took all that, you took government and history and English and
I enjoyed my course, and of course we had a brand new man out of West Point, Captain Moses, Lieutenant Moses.
He was promoted our junior year, I believe, to captain as a military instructor.
And he was captured by the active baton.
He was with a bunch of gorillas.
and somebody squealed on him, and they captured him and shot him.
But he was an awfully good officer.
Who were some of the other fine teachers you had during those four years?
Let me think a minute.
I took all the history of architecture I could take.
I took four courses under Charles Mattoon Brooks.
very slight built young man, but he was an excellent teacher.
And I liked the history of architecture much.
We didn't have history of landscape architecture.
So I took every course in history he had and loved them all.
And then Dr. Adriens and Mr. Bryson in horticulture.
Mr. Bryson was an excellent teacher and later a friend, and I went back.
And I can't think of who else.
Of course, chemistry didn't take on me.
I made a D and an E in chemistry.
Do you remember who the teacher was?
Dr. Potts.
Did he have a nickname?
No, that's Dr. Potts.
Later, when I was back at A&M on staff, Dick Fox was there.
This man, I had a lecture.
We had the big lecture hall at 8 o'clock in the morning.
I did.
And then we held the two labs.
But I didn't have any high school chemistry or anything like that.
The chemistry just didn't take on me.
I made a D the first semester.
And E the second semester.
And E meant that if you take a D quiz at the beginning of the next semester and make a C, no, make a D, it would be your grade.
So I got two Ds in freshman chemistry.
And I didn't take ag chemistry.
I'd never gotten out of A&M.
What about English?
I enjoyed English very much.
Who?
I had good English teachers in high school.
He coached the debate team, and I can't remember.
I don't remember my English teacher's name.
History?
Did you have any American history, European history?
You know, I can't remember their names.
I took 12 hours of education as electives, and it came in handy later.
Who did you turn to for advice and counsel if you needed...
Who was your favorite advisor?
We didn't know what an advisor was back in those days.
If you made 35 grade points your freshman year, you could take extra work.
And in spite of my two D's, I had 35 grade points.
So I said, well, I came here to go to school.
So I took, I was either in class or at work.
9 hours a day.
And I didn't have time for anything else.
All the requirement was that if you made 35 grade points, you'd take extra work.
And I didn't ask them how much, I just took it.
And I'd take 40 hours, and one of them a year, I took 44 hours.
Didn't ask anybody, didn't tell anybody.
Took it and made the best grade you ever made.

uh the what were the the what was the the rules or the typical pattern of behavior in class when you all went to class what you were you act like gentlemen you stayed there there was no disturbance uh when the when the military
The professor walked in, he stood at attention until he said, at ease.
No, there was no food around.
It was all business.
Did you ever go to sleep in class?
I probably did, but I don't remember when or what.
They were usually pretty interesting all the way.
We had several things happen that were really interesting.
They were in 1934.
Anybody told you about the Federal Transit Bureau yet?
Well, in the fall of 34, sometime during 34, the young men were hobos riding the rails all over the country.
So somebody decided that they ought to be in college, so the government will set up a program called the Federal Transit Bureau, and they'll take these kids and put them in school.
Lord have mercy.
They put them in Old Ross Hall, the worst dormitory on the campus, and it was four to the room and horrible showers and cottages.
That was the year that at midterm you could buy any file on campus because these boys knew them.
